response:
Let's denote the area of triangle $ABC$ as $A_{ABC}$, the area of triangle $BAD$ as $A_{BAD}$, and the area of triangle $CDE$ as $A_{CDE}$. The gray figure is the shaded area, which we'll call $G$. Then , 
\begin{align*}
A_{ABC}=A_{BAD}&=\tfrac{1}{2}\cdot\bfsf{6}\cdot\tfrac{1}{2}\bfsf{6}=\bfsf{\tfrac{1}{2}\bfsf{36}}=\bfsf{\tfrac{36}{2}(0.5)}=\bfsf{18(0.5)}=\bfsf{9}\\
A_{CDE}&=\tfrac{1}{2}\cdot\mathbfsf{6}\cdot\bfsf{6}=\bfsf{\tfrac{1}{2}(6\cdot 6)}=\bfsf{\tfrac{36}{2}}=\bfsf{18}\\
G&=A_{\text{outside triangles}}-A_{ABC}-A_{BAD}-A_{CDE}\\
&=A_{\text{outside triangles}}-A_{ABC}-A_{ABC}-A_{CDE}\\
&=A_{\text{outside triangles}}-2A_{ABC}-A_{CDE}\\
\end{align*}

Notice, we know that the sum of the areas of the four triangles surrounding the gray figure is equal to the sum of the areas of the two gray triangles, since the gray triangles fill the four surrounding triangles without overlapping. So $4G=A_{CDE}$, which we can plug in: 
\begin{align*}
A_{\text{outside triangles}}&=2G+A_{CDE}\\
&=2G+4G=6G\\
&=\mathbfsf{18}\\
\Rightarrow G&=\mathbf{3}
\end{align*}

However, this is not true since it is correct that the gray triangles fill the surrounding four triangles without overlapping, but their area sum is not necessarily equal to their surrounding area. The correct way to do it is the bellow:
\begin{align*}
G&=A_{\text{outside triangles}}-A_{ABC}-A_{BAD}-A_{CDE}\\
&=4G-4A_{CDE}(4)=\mathbfsf{10}G-4\mathbfsf{18}\\
\Rightarrow A_{G}&=\mathbf{\tfrac{10G-72}{9}}
\end{align*}


<answer> \tfrac{10}{9}</answer>

