The sine of the sum identity states that $\sin(A + B) = \sin A\cos B + \cos A\sin B$. 
Here, (\textit{for example}: $\sin \left( \theta + \frac{\pi}{4} \right) = \sin \theta \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) + \sin\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right)\cos \theta$)
  Taking into account that, $\sin \left( \frac{\pi}{4} \right) = \cos \left( \frac{\pi}{4} \right) = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}$, we get: $\sin \theta \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} + \cos \theta \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} = \frac{1}{3}$.
After simplifying this, we solve for $\sin \theta + \cos \theta$.\endthought
\begin{align*}
\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\sin \theta + \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\cos \theta  &= \frac{1}{3}\\
\sin \theta + \cos \theta  &= \frac{1}{3}\sqrt{2}.
\end{align*}
$\text{Taking the } \theta^2 \text{ of both sides}$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\sin^2 \theta + 2 \sin \theta \cos \theta + \cos^2 \theta  &= \frac{2}{9}\\
1 + \sin 2\theta  &= \frac{2}{9}\\
\sin 2\theta  &= \frac{2}{9} - 1 = - \frac{7}{9}.
\end{align*}
\begin{answer}-\frac{7}{9}
\end{answer}

