 Here we want the probability of getting at most two $6$s. Suppose we  assume there are $5$ trials each with a probability of $\frac{1}{6} i.e. P_{trial}=\frac{1}{6}$ of getting a $6$.There are four possibilities to consider. First , we may get a $6$ exactly zero times. Second , we may get a $6$ once. Ons third , we may get a $6$ twice.  For the first possibility, the probability is $\binom{5}{0}\times \frac{1}{6}^0\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^5$ whereas for the secont possibility it is $\binom{5}{1}\times \frac{1}{6}^1\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^4$. For the third possibility, the probability is $\binom{5}{2}\times \frac{1}{6}^2\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^3$. In fact, we have five mutually exclusive events forming the probability of getting at most two $6$s as the sum of the probabilities of the four events. So we need to calculate at least the first three probabilities. Having calculated the first three, the fourth probability will automatically give the fourth way .. this highlights multiple ways through which we need to calculate. I have mentioned you by four times instead of five to show that the only difference is having them reach the last trial.'$\binom{5}{k}\times \frac{1}{6}^k\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^{5-k}$
<answer>
\begin{align}
P(\text{At most two 6's})&=\binom{5}{0}\times \frac{1}{6}^0\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^5\qquad + \qquad \binom{5}{1}\times \frac{1}{6}^1\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^4\\
&\qquad + \qquad \binom{5}{2}\times \frac{1}{6}^2\times \left(1-\frac{1}{6}\right)^3\\
&=\binom{5}{0}\times 6^5+ \qquad \binom{5}{1}\times\qquad 7^4+ \qquad \binom{5}{2}\times \qquad 7^3
\end{align}
\end{answer}

